    <p><strong>Hot Off the Press </strong><br> by Dan Cole</p>
    When top-tier press members attend the International CES, they typically have a half-booked calendar before they even get to the show. They’ve lined up a variety of interviews and have a running list of exhibitors they want to see—be it the companies they’ve followed for years or the up-and-comers they’ve heard about but have never seen before. 
<P>Much of their ‘free’ time, however, is spent trolling the Alexis Park, the Las Vegas Hilton and the Las Vegas Convention Center inside and out, looking for the big story of the day—or even better—the big story of the year. </P>
<P>I bet it’s safe for me to assume that on every CES exhibitors’ wish list is actually BEING that one big story. We very much want that for you, too. </P>
<P>That’s why I’m proud to announce our new-and-improved press reception, <STRONG>CES Unveiled: The Official Press Event of the International CES. </STRONG>Here, media and analysts check out exclusive tabletop demonstrations and network with today's hottest tech companies almost two days before the show doors open. This is an incredible way for you to be heard and seen, <EM>first,</EM> and gain the top-of-mind awareness you want. </P>
<P>Only credentialed media and analysts are allowed to attend this event, which includes the likes of <EM>NBC Today Show,</EM> CNN, ABC News, Bloomberg News, <EM>Business Week, Wired, Maxim</EM> and <EM>Rolling Stone, </EM>alongside the top names in international trade and consumer press. Plus, the 2005 event will be filmed for CES’ satellite video news release for distribution to broadcast stations nationwide. </P>
<P>Previously reserved for Innovations Honorees, this event is now a potential attention-grabber for all exhibitors. Participation opportunities are now made available to our exhibitors on a first-come, first-served basis. There are a variety of sponsorships available for this three-hour event, and you can <A href="/print/press/events/default.asp">get the details online</A>. </P>
<P>With more than 2,400 exhibitors in the International CES, media and analysts will get a pre-show look at who will be making news headlines before the show even begins. Don’t miss your opportunity to be in the media’s minds, eyes and ears right from the start—and increase the odds that you are, in fact, that one big story.</P>
